📚 Identity & Authentication - Quick Revision Notes (Manager Meeting)


---

1. Identity

Identity = Who you are

Examples:

User (Suresh)

Employee ID

Email

Service Account

Application


Identity is claimed, not yet verified.


---

2. Authentication

Authentication = Proving who you are

Question answered:

> "Who are you?"



Examples:

Password

MFA

Fingerprint

Certificate


Authentication verifies identity.


---

3. Authorization

Authorization = What you're allowed to do

Question answered:

> "What can you access?"



Example:

User logs in successfully

↓

Can Read ✔

Can Write ✔

Can Delete ✖

Authentication can succeed while authorization fails.


---

4. Credentials

Credentials prove identity.

Examples:

Password

OTP

Certificate

Private Key

Smart Card


Identity ≠ Credential


---

5. Principal

A Principal is any entity that can authenticate.

Examples:

User

Service

Application

API

Claude

MCP Server



---

6. Session

Session remembers an authenticated user.

Traditional Web

Login

↓

Session Created

↓

Browser Stores Cookie

↓

Cookie Sent

↓

Server Finds Session


---

7. Token

Token proves authentication already happened.

Password

↓

Authenticate

↓

Token

↓

Used for API calls

Never send passwords on every request.


---

8. Claims

Claims are information inside tokens.

Examples:

Name

Email

Role

Groups

Department


Claims help authorization.


---

9. Authentication Flow

Identity

↓

Credentials

↓

Authentication

↓

Token Issued

↓

Claims

↓

Authorization

↓

Access Granted


